@MOL
I have not--those are the crime novels set in Ancient Rome, right? Are they worthwhile reading? (They must be, or you wouldn't mention them.)
I read the somewhat historical/somewhat fantastical novel *Lavinia*  by Ursula LeGuin, when it first came out. It bothered me that she had Lavinia dress in a toga, and I nearly wrote to Ms. LeGuin to complain (but also to praise the novel as a whole.) Then a little digging informed me that in VERY early Rome, togae were worn by men and women alike. Still wish I had written, though--I would have probably received a response, and now that LeGuin has passed away, I won't get the chance.

